Throughout his career, Oskar Eustis has been dedicated to the development of new plays and the classics as a director, dramaturg and producer. Among the plays he's helped bring into being, you can count Angels in America, the Tony-winning Hamilton and Fun Home, with more new work constantly on the bubble. Throughout his career, he has also produced and directed Shakespeare in venues around the US, from prisons to Broadway, including The Public's 2017 free Shakespeare in the Park staging of Julius Ceasar that generated a national conversation.

Eustis has also directed the world premieres of plays by Philip Kan Gotanda, David Henry Hwang, Emily Mann, Suzan-Lori Parks, Ellen McLaughlin and Eduardo Machado, among many others. He's a professor of dramatic writing and arts and public policy at New York University and has held professorships at UCLA, Middlebury College and Brown University, where he founded and chaired the Trinity Rep/Brown University consortium for professional theater training. He has been Artistic Director of The Public Theater in New York since 2005.

author: Oskar_Eustis;
title: Why theater is essential to democracy

aws-transcripts.transcript: theater matters because democracy matters. Theater is the essential art form of democracy. And we know this because they were born in the same city in the late sixth century BC. The idea of Western democracy was born. It was, of course, Ah, very partial and flawed democracy. But the idea that power should stem from the consent of the governed, that power should flow from below to above, not the other way around was born in that decade. And in that same decade, somebody legend has it. Somebody named Festus invented the idea of dialogue. What does that mean to invent dialogue? Well, we know that the Festival of Dionysus gather the entire citizenry of Athens on the side of the Acropolis, and they would listen to music. They would watch dancing and they would have stories told as part of the festival of Dionysus. And storytelling is much like what's happening right now. I'm standing up here, the unitary authority, and I'm talking to you and you were sitting back and you're receiving what I have to say, and you may disagree with it. You may think I'm an insufferable fool. You may be bored to death, but that dialogue is mostly taking place inside your own head. But what happens if instead of me talking to you and Festus thought of this, I just shift 90 degrees to the left, and I talked to another person on stage with May. Everything changes because at that moment I'm not the possessor of truth. I'm a guy with an opinion, and I'm talking to somebody else. And you know what? That other person has an opinion, too. And it's drama. Remember conflict? They disagree with May. There's a conflict between two points of view, and the D thesis of that is that the truth can only emerge in the conflict of different points of view. It's not the possession of any one person. And if you believe in democracy, you have to believe that if you don't believe that you're an autocrat who's putting up with democracy. But that's the basic thesis of democracy that the conflict of different points of views leads to the truth. What's the other thing that's happening? I'm not asking you to sit back and listen to May. I'm ask you to lean forward and imagine my point of view what this looks like and feels like to me as a character and then and ask you to switch your mind and imagine what it feels like to the other person talking. I'm asking you to exercise empathy and the idea that truth comes from the collision of different ideas and the emotional muscle of empathy or the necessary tools for democratic citizenship. What else happens and the third thing really is you is the community itself is the audience, and you know from personal experience that when you go to the movies, you walk into a movie theater, and if it's empty, you're delighted because nothing is going to be between you and the movie you can spread out. Put your legs over the top of the stadium, seats each of popcorn and just enjoy it. But if you walk into a live theater and you see that the theaters have full, your heart sinks. You're disappointed immediately because whether you knew it or not, you're coming to that theater to be part of an audience. You're coming to have the collective experience of laughing together, crying to their holding your breath together to see what's gonna happen next. You may have walked into that theater as an individual consumer. But if the theater does its job, you've walked out with the sense of yourself as part of a whole as part of a community that's built into the D. N A. Of my art form. 2500 years later, Joe Path decided that the culture should belong to everybody in the United States of America, and there was his job to try to deliver on that promise. He created free Shakespeare in the Park and Free Shakespeare in the Park is based on a very simple idea. The idea that the best theater, the best art that we can produce should go to everybody and belong to everybody. And to this day, every summer night in Central Park, 2000 people are winding up to see the best theater we can provide for free. It's not a commercial transaction. In 1967 13 years after he figured that out, he figured out something else, which is that the Democratic Circle was not complete by just giving the people the classics. We had to actually let the people create their own classics and take this stage. And so in 1967 Joe opened the public theater downtown on Astor Place, and the first show he ever produced was the world premiere of Hair. First Thing I ever did It wasn't Shakespeare, Clive Barnes in the Time said that resist, Mr Pap took a broom and swept up all the refugees from the each village streets on the stage at the public. He didn't mean it complimentary Lei, but Joe put it up in the lobby he was so proud of, and what the Public Theater did over the next years with amazing shows like For Colored Girls who have considered suicide When The Rainbow is Enough, the Chorus Line and perhaps even hears the most extraordinary example, I can think of Larry Kramer's savage cry of rage about the AIDS crisis, the normal heart. Because when Joe produced that play in 1985 there was Maur information about AIDS in Frank Rich's review in The New York Times than The New York Times had published in the previous four years. Larry was actually changing the dialogue about AIDS through writing this play, and Joe was by producing, and I was blessed to commission and work on Tony Kushner's Angels in America. And when doing that play and along with normal heart, we could see that the culture was actually shifting. It wasn't caused by the theater, but the theater was doing its part to change what it meant to be gay in the United States. And I'm incredibly proud of that. On I took over Joe's old job at the public in 2005 I realized one of the problems we had was a victim of our own success, which is Shakespeare in the Park had been founded as a program for access, and it was now the hardest ticket to get in New York City. People slept out for two nights to get those tickets. What was that doing that was eliminating 98% of the population from even considering going toe it? So we re founded the mobile unit and took Shakespeare to prisons, to homeless shelters, to community centers in all five boroughs and even in New Jersey and Westchester County. And that program proved something to us that we knew intuitively. People's need for theater is as powerful as their desire for food or for drink.
